  "prompt": "Why should I tip my server?",
  "response": "Tipping in the United States is a complex issue rooted in historical and cultural practices. Here's a breakdown of the key reasons why tipping is expected and considered important for servers:\n\n*   **Low Base Wages:** In many states, servers are paid a significantly lower minimum wage than other workers, sometimes as low as $2.13 per hour. This is because employers are allowed to count tips towards meeting the regular minimum wage. If tips don't reach that level, the employer is supposed to make up the difference, but this isn't always enforced.\n\n*   **Supplementing Income:** Tips are intended to be a crucial part of a server's income, making up the difference between their low base wage and a livable wage.\n\n*   **Service Incentive:** Tipping can serve as an incentive for servers to provide good service. Customers are more likely to tip well when they feel they have received attentive and friendly service.\n\n*   **Industry Standard:** Tipping is deeply ingrained in the restaurant industry and is expected by both servers and customers. Not tipping, especially for acceptable service, can be seen as rude or disrespectful.\n\n*   **Cultural Norm:** Tipping is a cultural norm in the US. It is widely practiced and considered part of the dining experience.\n\n**Things to Consider:**\n\n*   **Service Quality:** While tipping is expected, the amount you tip can reflect the quality of service you received. Exceptional service may warrant a higher tip, while poor service may justify a lower tip (but generally not no tip at all, unless the service was truly terrible).\n*   **Alternatives:** Some restaurants are moving away from traditional tipping models and instead implementing service charges or higher menu prices to pay their employees a living wage. If you see this, tipping may not be expected or necessary.\n*   **Fairness:** The tipping system has its critics, who argue that it can be discriminatory and lead to income instability for servers. Discussions about alternatives to tipping are ongoing.\n*   **Other workers:** It's also important to remember that in some restaurants, servers share their tips with other staff, such as bussers and bartenders.\n\n**In Summary:**\n\nTipping is an integral part of the dining culture in the US, serving as a way to supplement servers' low wages and incentivize good service. While the system has its flaws and is subject to ongoing debate, it remains the standard practice in most restaurants.",
